Chaetal morphology (

). Dorsal ordinary chaetae of five 
types
: Ml (

a–b), Mc (

), Mcc (

), me (

e–f) and mi (

). S-chaetae on terga thin, smooth, shorter than Ml and longer than Mc (

).

Buccal cone moderately developed. Labrum truncated, chaetal formula as 2/4, 2 (adult) or 4/4, 2 (juvenile). Labium with 11 chaetae and 
2 x
(

). Mandible complicated (

), consisting of 2 rami, 2 definite teeth and some spine-like chaetae. Small ramus consisting of one spine-like chaeta and 7–8 slender chaetae, large ramus developed, with 2 rows of marginal chaetae, 4 strong and spine-like chaetae, marginal chaetae on ramus simple, bifurcated or tri-furcated, about 9-12 spine-like chaetae present on the central area of basal part of the large ramus. The longer ramus about 10 times as long as the small one. Maxilla consisting of two lamellae, the inner lamella much shorter than the outer one, with two minute apical teeth, the outer one with marginal filaments on inner side (

). On ventral side of head, group Vi with 6+6 chaetae, groups Vea, Vem and Vep with 4, 3 and 2 chaetae respectively. Dorsal tubercles and chaetotaxy of head as in 
Tab. 1
. and 

. Dorsal central area with 6 separate tubercles; one tubercle Cl, 2 An, one Fr and 2 Oc, chaeta O absent. Dorsal posterior area with 4 separate tubercles: 2 Di and 2 De. Line of chaetae Di2–De2 crosses line Di1– De1 on head (cross-type, 
Deharveng 1983
). Dorsal lateral area with 1 fused tubercle (Dl+L+So).

